<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Len Hal; Jerry Hicks, ; Chris Foster 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 NEW HIGH: Thirty-two people are recorded as having climbed the highest peaks 
in all 50 states. But nobody as quickly as a Balboa Island psychotherapist, who 
has an amputated leg. Todd Huston, 33, started his odyssey June 1 and on Sunday 
reached the top of Hawaii's Mauna Kea (13,796 feet). Huston, who lost his right 
leg below the knee at age 21, reached all 50 peaks within 68 days, bettering 
the record of 101 days. . . . Alaska's 20,320-foot Mt. McKinley was the 
toughest, he says. "It usually takes 14 to 18 days, if you make it at all. We 
took 12 days." 
</P>
<P>
 LAST TIME: The 50-day baseball strike in 1981 actually turned out well for 
Angel fans. (C1) . . . The Baltimore Orioles' Doug DeCinces was the American 
League player representative during negotiations and was later traded to 
California in what many saw as retribution. He joined other key union figures, 
such as Bob Boone and Reggie Jackson, to form the nucleus of an Angels team 
that took the AL West in 1982. Angel general manager "Buzzie Bavasi had some 
insight," said DeCinces, a Corona del Mar resident. "We were active in the 
strike, but we could help a team win." 
</P>
<P>
 DAVE'S WORLD: TV producer Dave Forman, whose company is based in Irvine, is a 
veteran of reality shows. For six years he produced "On Scene: Emergency 
Response." Now he's producer-host on a new venture, "Special Access," which 
started daily at 5:30 p.m. this week on KCAL-TV . . . . It has stories about 
real life, just not emergencies. Says Forman, who lives in San Clemente: "I 
like to take viewers places they can't go on their own." 
</P>
<P>
 STILL PICKING: At age 12, Gordon McClelland (E1) had a job picking oranges 
near his hometown of Villa Park. While the county's citrus groves have 
practically disappeared, McClellan's fascination with the paper labels on old 
orange crates has only grown. Now it is antique dealers who go "picking" for 
these labels, and McClelland, 43, has parlayed his interest into a life's work, 
not just buying and selling the colorful labels, but writing books as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
