<HEADLINE>
<P>
DOMENICO MODUGNO; RECORDED 'VOLARE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Domenico Modugno, 66, Italian pop singer who gained fame in the United States 
with his hit "Volare." Although critics viewed the singer as only a good 
guitarist, Modugno won awards at Italy's prestigious San Remo Music Festival 
two years in a row by singing his own compositions.The first in 1958 was "Nel 
Blu Dipinto di Blu," which means "In the Blue Sky Painted Blue," better known 
in the United States for one of its lyrics, "Volare" or "To Fly." In 1959, he 
won with "Piove" meaning "It Rains," but that Italian hit did not translate to 
additional sales or fame in the United States. Popular in Italy from 1953 to 
1976, Modugno also recorded an Italian version of "Mack the Knife." He was 
involved in politics and in 1987 was elected to the national Chamber of 
Deputies on the Radical Party ticket. On Saturday on the Italian island of 
Lampedusa of an apparent heart attack. 
</P>
