 The NHL, without a collective bargaining agreement since Sept. 15, 1993, will 
meet with the players' association for the first time in five months on Aug. 
18. Free agency and a salary cap are expected to be on an agenda that includes 
a 16-point rollback that would eliminate meal allowances and have players pay 
their way to training camp and home again at the end of the season, according 
to the union. College Football 
</P>
<P>
 Cotton Bowl officials are scheduled to meet this week to consider options for 
the 58-year-old event, which was left out of the Tier I bowl alliance. 
