<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LAGUNA HILLS; COUNCIL TO WEIGH STOP SIGN INSTALLATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council tonight will consider placing a stop sign at the intersection 
of Hon Avenue and Camberwell Street, just off of Alicia Parkway. 
</P>
<P>
 Area residents have long complained about drivers speeding down the 
residential street that begins at Alicia Parkway as a commercial strip. 
</P>
<P>
 The traffic commission has recommended a second stop sign, at Hon and Julie 
avenues. The recommendation comes just weeks after the council approved new 
three-way stop signs along Mackenzie Street. 
</P>
<P>
 A group of vocal Mackenzie residents had banded together to ask the council to 
slow down the commuters who use it as a freeway alternate. 
</P>
<P>
 City Engineer Ken Rosenfield had recommended only a stop sign at Hon and 
Camberwell because it is difficult for drivers to see the intersection as they 
travel south on Hon. 
</P>
<P>
 He did not recommend a second stop sign at Hon and Julie because stop signs 
are not used just to slow traffic. 
</P>
<P>
 The council will also consider placing a rumble strip on Hon north of 
Camberwell to further slow drivers. LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
