<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: BANKING & FINANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 T-Bills Hit 4-Week High: The Treasury sold $12.4 billion of new three-month 
bills at an average discount rate of 4.43%, up from 4.35% last week.Another 
$12.5 billion of new six-month bills sold at an average discount rate of 4.93%, 
up from 4.75%. The three-month-bill rate was the highest since they sold for 
4.50% on July 11. The six-month bill rate was the highest since they averaged 
4.94% the same day. The new discount rates understate the actual return to 
investors: 4.54% for three-month bills, with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,888, 
and 5.13% for a six-month bill selling for $9,750.80. The discount rate 
reflects the price discount received when government securities are purchased 
at less than face value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
