<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHERE ARE THEY NOW?; MIKE MARSHALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times staff writer David W. Myers catches up with former Dodgers and Angels. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An eccentric right-hander who holds a doctorate in kinesiology, Marshall 
relieved in a record 106 games in 1974 -- his first year with the Dodgers -- 
leading the club to the pennant and earning the Cy Young Award.Beset by 
injuries in 1975, his 14 losses in relief set another record and he was traded 
to Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
 Until recently, Marshall was the baseball coach and a physical education 
professor at West Texas A&M. His contract was not renewed in June, and the 
grievance he filed was turned down on Monday. At 51, he still pitches regularly 
in a semi-pro league and also works as a consultant for several major league 
clubs. 
</P>
